        <TextBlock HorizontalAlignment="Left" Margin="403,7,-1,0" TextWrapping="Wrap" VerticalAlignment="Top" Height="671" Width="486" IsEnabled="False"><Run FontWeight="Bold" Text="Small signal analysis of balanced differential amplifiers"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="The small signal characteristics of balanced differential amplifiers, take an example of emitter coupled pair and source coupled pair."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Span FontWeight="Bold"><Run Text="Differential mode gain:"/></Span><Span><Run Text="  Adm  = Change in the differential output voltage per unit change in the differential input voltage.    Adm = Vod/ Vid "/></Span><LineBreak/><Span FontWeight="Bold"><Run Text="Common mode gain:"/></Span><Span><Run Text=" Acm = Change in the common mode output voltage per unit change in the common mode input voltage. Acm = Voc/ Vic"/></Span><LineBreak/><Span FontWeight="Bold"><Run Text="Differential mode to common mode gain:   "/></Span><Span><Run Text="Adm-cm is the change in the common-mode output voltage per unit change in the differential input voltage."/></Span><Span FontWeight="Bold"><Run Text="  "/></Span><Span><Run Text="Adm-cm = Voc/ Vid"/></Span><LineBreak/><Span FontWeight="Bold"><Run Text="Common mode to differential mode gain: "/></Span><Span><Run Text="Acm-dm is the change in the differential mode output voltage per unit change in the common-mode input.   Acm-dm = Vod/Vic"/></Span><LineBreak/><Span FontWeight="Bold"><Run Text="CMRR (Common mode rejection ratio)"/></Span><Run Text=" = |Adm / Acm | = Desired differential mode gain to the unwanted common mode gain.   "/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="12" Text="Slew Rate: "/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="12" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="The slew rate of the CMOS differential amplifier depends on the amount of current that can be sourced or sinked into the compensating capacitor. Slew rate = Iss/C where C is the total capacitance connected to the output node.    If Iss = 10uA and c = 5pF, slew rate is 2 V/us.   "/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="Noise performance: "/><LineBreak/><Run FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="At low frequencies, 1/f noise is important and at high frequencies low currents, thermal noise is important."/><LineBreak/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" Text="Performance of differential amplifiers: "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="A key attribute to analyzing the performance of differential amplifiers is the minimum dc     and ac differential voltage that can be analyzed. Due to component mismatches and drifts       of component values with temperature, dc differential voltages at the output creates distortion to the dc component of the signal that is being amplified. Hence causing a non zero"/><Run FontWeight="Bold" Text=" "/><Run Text="Adm-cm and Acm-dm.   The resolution distortion caused by common mode inputs to differential output can limit the overall resolution of the system. Hence reducing these offset errors is essential to analog circuits. "/><Span><Run Text="The frequency response of the CMOS differential amplifiers is due to the various parasitic capacitors at each node of the circuit.  "/></Span><Run Text=" The most important source of offset error in the emitter coupled pair are the mismatches in the base"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="width, base doping level and the collector doping level of the transistors."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="For MOS differential amplifiers: The input offset current is the difference between the two gate currents and is essentially zero because the gates of the input transistors are connected to an insulator i.e silicon dioxide."/><LineBreak/><Run Text="However, since MOS transistors exhibit lower transconductance than bipolar transistors at the same current, they display a less accurate input offset voltage and CMRR compared to bipolar transistors.  "/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><LineBreak/><LineBreak/><LineBreak/></TextBlock>
        <TextBlock HorizontalAlignment="Left" Margin="421,527,0,0" TextWrapping="Wrap" VerticalAlignment="Top"/>
        <TextBlock HorizontalAlignment="Left" Margin="30,393,0,0" TextWrapping="Wrap" VerticalAlignment="Top" Height="294" Width="333"><Run FontWeight="Bold" Text="Offset Drift Voltage "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="When emitter coupled pair are utilized in low level dc amplifiers the offset voltage is critical .  You can manually adjust the input offset voltage to zero with a potentiometer."/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Now the variation of this offset voltage with temperature is referred to as drift.  For emitter coupled ckt:  "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="change in Vos / change in temperature  = Vos / T."/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Where Vos is the input offset voltage."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="For Source Coupled Pair: "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="The MOS transistors inherently provide higher input resistance and lower input bias current than bipolar transistors when the MOS gate is used as the input.  "/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Current vs voltage amplifiers:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Input and output resistance is large for MOSFET voltage amplifiers.  With low input resistance and a small output load the output variable can be current, hence a current amplifier."/><LineBreak/><Run/></TextBlock>

